    "reasoning": "To implement a JK flip-flop, I need to follow the given truth table. The behavior of the JK flip-flop is defined as follows:\n1. When J=0 and K=0, the output Q remains unchanged (Qold).\n2. When J=0 and K=1, the output Q is set to 0.\n3. When J=1 and K=0, the output Q is set to 1.\n4. When J=1 and K=1, the output Q toggles (Qold is inverted).\n\nThe implementation requires sequential logic using a positive edge-triggered clock. A D flip-flop can be used to implement the JK flip-flop by calculating the next state (D) from the current state and inputs (J, K). The next state D should be equal to the desired next value of Q according to the truth table.\n\nSteps:\n1. Declare the module with proper input/output ports.\n2. Use a flip-flop (register) to store the previous output Q.\n3. Inside the always block, compute the next value of Q based on J and K inputs according to the truth table.\n4. Assign this computed value to the flip-flop on the positive clock edge.\n\nFor avoiding syntax errors:\n1. Use logic type for all signals.\n2. Declare all signals explicitly.\n3. Use always @(posedge clk) for sequential behavior.\n4. Use always @(*) for combinational logic if needed.\n5. Avoid using reserved words as identifiers.\n6. Ensure the module interface exactly matches the provided one.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input clk,\n    input j,\n    input k,\n    output logic Q\n);\n\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (j == 1'b0 && k == 1'b0)\n            Q <= Q; // Hold previous value\n        else if (j == 1'b0 && k == 1'b1)\n            Q <= 1'b0; // Reset\n        else if (j == 1'b1 && k == 1'b0)\n            Q <= 1'b1; // Set\n        else\n            Q <= ~Q; // Toggle\n    end\n\nendmodule"
